{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17614302","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17614302"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T14:43:34+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T14:43:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16357"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16357","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16357"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0.12,0.2,0.56,0.12]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9048"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64851"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9048","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9048"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16357"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50285"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"7184"},{"type":"tags","id":"7195"},{"type":"tags","id":"7258"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21515"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21518"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64851","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/64851"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following cranial nerves exits through the foramen ovale?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Oculomotor nerve (CN III)","Ophthalmic nerve (CN V1)","Maxillary nerve (CN V2)","Mandibular nerve (CN V3)","Facial nerve (CN VII)"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe foramen ovale is an opening in the greater wing of the sphenoid bone that transmits the \u003Cstrong\u003Emandibular nerve (CN V3)\u003C/strong\u003E, which is the third division of the trigeminal nerve. This nerve carries both sensory fibres from the lower face and motor fibres to the muscles of mastication.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eoculomotor nerve (CN III)\u003C/strong\u003E exits the skull through the superior orbital fissure, not the foramen ovale. It supplies most of the extraocular muscles and carries parasympathetic fibres to the pupil.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eophthalmic nerve (CN V1)\u003C/strong\u003E also passes through the superior orbital fissure. It provides sensory innervation to the upper third of the face, including the forehead and upper eyelid.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Emaxillary nerve (CN V2)\u003C/strong\u003E exits through the foramen rotundum. It provides sensory innervation to the middle third of the face, including the cheek and upper teeth.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Efacial nerve (CN VII)\u003C/strong\u003E exits the skull through the internal acoustic meatus and stylomastoid foramen. It provides motor innervation to the muscles of facial expression and carries taste fibres from the anterior two-thirds of the tongue.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The mandibular branch of the trigeminal nerve (CN V3) exits the skull through the foramen ovale.","The foramen ovale is located in the greater wing of the sphenoid bone.","Understanding cranial nerve exit points is crucial for localising neurological lesions."],"references":["Batra AP, Mahajan A, Gupta K. Marginal mandibular branch of the facial nerve: An anatomical study. Indian J Plast Surg. 2010 Jan;43(1):60-4. doi: 10.4103/0970-0358.63968. PMID: 20924452; PMCID: PMC2938626.","Netter, F. H. (2015). Netter\u2019s Cranial Nerve Collection E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Singh, V. 